    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-05-03T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-05-03T22:00:00-05:00" n="383"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d383">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00 B/306: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract—Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-05-04T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 4, 1927—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 4—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>518. The following has been received from the American consul at Canton:</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Reliable information has been received by me to the effect that General Li
                        Chai-sum<note n="55" xml:id="d383fn55">Also known as Li Chi-shen, military
                        commander of Canton and supporter of Chiang Kai-shek in Kwangtung
                        Province.</note> is in serious need of arms and ammunition <pb facs="0435"
                        n="327" xml:id="pg_327"/> at this time. Cancelation of the arms embargo
                        agreement<note n="56" xml:id="d383fn56">See <ref target="frus1919v01#pg_667">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1919, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 667</ref> ff.</note> is favored by many
                    foreigners as being much fairer to all parties concerned than is the existing
                    situation. The political groups most friendly to us are adversely affected by
                    the present situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
